 generation that initiated this break with precedent. The compilers of the Summa Halensis first articulated many positions that eventually become closely associated with the Franciscan tradition on issues like the nature of God, the proof for God's existence, free will, the transcendentals, and Christology. This book is essential reading for anyone wishing to understand the ways in which medieval thinkers employed philosophical concepts in a theological context as well as the evolution of Franciscan thought and its legacy to modernity.A Reader in Early Franciscan Theology is available from the publisher on an open-access basis.  afunded by King's College, UK  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aTheology, DoctrinalvEarly works to 1800. 4aMedieval Studies. 4aPhilosophy & Theory. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Religious.2bisacsh  aAlexander of Hales.  aChristology.  aFranciscan.  aJohn of La Rochelle.  aTrinity.  adivine infinity.  afree will.  amedieval philosophy.  amedieval theology.  amoral law.  aontological argument.  atranscendentals.1 aBychkov, Oleg, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSchumacher, Lydia, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt2 aKing's College, UKefunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2022 Englishz978311099276208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK